{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_1","type":"agent_message","text":"**Topology Summary**\n\nSingle-supply inverting op amp differentiator on a 5 V rail. `Vin` is the triangle-wave input node, capacitively coupled through `C1` into the op amp inverting input node, e.g. `NINV`. `Vout` is the op amp output. The non-inverting input is tied to a mid-supply reference `Vref = 2.5 V`, so the circuit differentiates around `Vref` instead of ground.\n\nExpected behavior:\n\n`Vout â‰ˆ Vref - Rf*C1*dVin/dt`\n\nA rising ramp at `Vin` drives `Vout` below `Vref`; a falling ramp drives `Vout` above `Vref`, producing a square-like transient waveform limited by the 0 V and 5 V rails.\n\n**Device/Function List**\n\n- `VDD` independent DC source: 5 V supply from `VDD` to `0`.\n- `Vin` independent voltage source: triangle waveform from `Vin` to `0`, centered around `Vref`.\n- Vref divider: two equal resistors from `VDD` to `Vref` and from `Vref` to `0`.\n- Op amp primitive/macromodel: powered from `VDD` and `0`, non-inverting input at `Vref`, inverting input at `NINV`, output at `Vout`.\n- `C1`: from `Vin` to `NINV`, nominally 10 nF.\n- `Rf`: from `Vout` to `NINV`, nominally 10 kOhm.\n- Optional DC leakage resistor: very large resistor from `NINV` to `Vref` only for convergence, much larger than `Rf`.\n\n**Bias/Reference Strategy**\n\nUse `Vref = 2.5 V` as the signal common-mode reference. The op amp forces `NINV` to behave as a virtual `Vref` node during linear operation. The triangle source at `Vin` should be centered around 2.5 V with modest amplitude so the differentiated output remains mostly inside the 0 V to 5 V supply range.\n\n**Signal Or Feedback Path**\n\nInput current is generated by `C1` according to the slope of `Vin`. That current flows into the virtual-reference node `NINV` and is converted to output voltage through feedback resistor `Rf`. The feedback path is purely resistive from `Vout` to `NINV`, giving differentiator behavior with inversion.\n\n**SPICE/Netlist Constraints**\n\n- Final file should be `p25.cir`.\n- Preserve node names exactly: `Vin`, `Vout`.\n- `Vin` must be driven by an explicit independent triangle-wave voltage source.\n- `Vout` must be the op amp output node.\n- Include transient analysis: `.tran 1u 10m`.\n- If using a behavioral op amp, its output must be limited between 0 V and 5 V.\n- Stay within primitive-device/macromodel assumptions; do not replace the differentiator with a controlled-source shortcut unless implementing the op amp itself.\n\n**Failure Risks To Avoid**\n\n- Do not center `Vin` around 0 V; this breaks the single-supply bias assumption.\n- Do not tie the non-inverting op amp input to ground; it must use `Vref`.\n- Do not omit a DC path or convergence aid if the simulator struggles with the capacitive input node.\n- Do not make the optional `NINV`-to-`Vref` resistor comparable to `Rf`; it would corrupt differentiator gain.\n- Do not choose triangle slope, `Rf`, or `C1` so large that `Vout` is permanently railed unless visible clipping is intended.\n- Do not swap polarity: rising `Vin` should produce lower `Vout`, falling `Vin` should produce higher `Vout`."}}
